1 Section 1. Section 18-1736, Reissue Revised Statutes of Nebraska, is
2 amended to read:
3 18-1736 (1) A city or village may designate parking spaces,
4 including access aisles, for the exclusive use of (a) handicapped or
5 disabled persons whose motor vehicles display the distinguishing license
6 plates issued to handicapped or disabled persons pursuant to the Motor
7 Vehicle Registration Act section 60-3,113, (b) handicapped or disabled
8 persons whose motor vehicles display a distinguishing license plate
9 issued to a handicapped or disabled person by another state, (c) such
10 other handicapped or disabled persons or temporarily handicapped or
11 disabled persons whose motor vehicles display a handicapped or disabled
12 parking permit, and (d) such other motor vehicles which display a
13 handicapped or disabled parking permit.
14 (2) If a city or village so designates a parking space or access
15 aisle, it shall be indicated by posting aboveground and immediately
16 adjacent to and visible from each space or access aisle a sign as
17 described in section 18-1737. In addition to such sign, the space or
18 access aisle may also be indicated by blue paint on the curb or edge of
19 the paved portion of the street adjacent to the space or access aisle.
20 (3) For purposes of sections 18-1736 to 18-1741.07:
21 (a) Access aisle has the same meaning as in section 60-302.01;
22 (b) Handicapped or disabled parking permit has the same meaning as
23 in section 60-331.01;
24 (c) Handicapped or disabled person has the same meaning as in
25 section 60-331.02; and
26 (d) Temporarily handicapped or disabled person has the same meaning
27 as in section 60-352.01.
28 Sec. 2. Section 28-306, Revised Statutes Supplement, 2025, is
29 amended to read:
30 28-306 (1) A person who causes the death of another unintentionally
31 while engaged in the operation of a motor vehicle in violation of the law
-3-

LB972 LB972
2026 2026
1 of the State of Nebraska or in violation of any city or village ordinance
2 commits motor vehicle homicide.
3 (2) Except as provided in subsection (3) of this section, motor
4 vehicle homicide is a Class I misdemeanor.
5 (3)(a) If the proximate cause of the death of another is the
6 operation of a motor vehicle in violation of section 60-6,213 or
7 60-6,214, motor vehicle homicide is a Class IIIA felony.
8 (b) If the proximate cause of the death of another is the operation
9 of a motor vehicle in violation of section 60-6,196 or 60-6,197.06, motor
10 vehicle homicide is a Class IIA felony.
11 (c) If the proximate cause of the death of another is the operation
12 of a motor vehicle in violation of section 60-6,196 or 60-6,197.06, motor
13 vehicle homicide is a Class II felony if the defendant has a prior
14 conviction for a violation of section 60-6,196 or 60-6,197.06, under a
15 city or village ordinance enacted in conformance with section 60-6,196,
16 or under a law of another state if, at the time of the conviction under
17 the law of such other state, the offense for which the defendant was
18 convicted would have been a violation of section 60-6,196.
19 (4)(a) For a conviction under subsection (2) or subdivision (3)(a)
20 of this section, the court may, as part of the judgment of conviction,
21 order the person not to drive any motor vehicle for any purpose for a
22 period of up to two years and order that the operator's license of such
23 person be revoked suspended for the same period.
24 (b) For a conviction under subdivision (3)(b) or (c) of this
25 section, the court shall, as part of the judgment of conviction, order
26 the person not to drive any motor vehicle for any purpose for a period of
27 fifteen years and shall order that the operator's license of such person
28 be revoked for the same period.
29 (5) An order of the court described in this section shall be
30 administered upon sentencing, upon final judgment of any appeal or
31 review, or upon the date that any probation is revoked.
-4-

LB972 LB972
2026 2026
1 (6) The crime punishable under this section shall be treated as a
2 separate and distinct offense from any other offense arising out of acts
3 alleged to have been committed while the person was in violation of this
4 section.
5 Sec. 3. Section 37-1278.01, Reissue Revised Statutes of Nebraska, is
6 amended to read:
7 37-1278.01 (1) The Department of Motor Vehicles shall issue a bonded
8 certificate of title to an applicant who:
9 (a) Presents evidence reasonably sufficient to satisfy the
10 department of the applicant's ownership of the motorboat or security
11 interest in the motorboat;
12 (b) Pays a fee of fifty dollars for motorboats manufactured on or
13 after January 1, 1990, and twenty dollars for motorboats manufactured
14 prior to January 1, 1990; and
15 (c) Files a bond in a form prescribed by the department and executed
16 by the applicant; and .
17 (d) Provides proof that written notice as prescribed in subsection
18 (6) of this section has been provided to each party with a secured
19 interest in the motorboat.
20 (2) The bond shall be issued by a surety company authorized to
21 transact business in this state, in an amount equal to one and one-half
22 times the value of the motorboat as determined by the department using
23 reasonable appraisal methods, and conditioned to indemnify any prior
24 owner and secured party, any subsequent purchaser and secured party, and
25 any successor of the purchaser and secured party for any expense, loss,
26 or damage, including reasonable attorney's fees, incurred by reason of
27 the issuance of the certificate of title to the motorboat or any defect
28 in or undisclosed security interest upon the right, title, and interest
29 of the applicant in and to the motorboat. An interested person may have a
30 cause of action to recover on the bond for a breach of the conditions of
31 the bond. The aggregate liability of the surety to all persons having a
-5-

LB972 LB972
2026 2026
1 claim shall not exceed the amount of the bond.
2 (3) At the end of three years after the issuance of the bond, the
3 holder of the certificate of title may apply to the department on a form
4 prescribed by the department for the release of the bond and the removal
5 of the notice required by subsection (4) of this section if no claim has
6 been made on the bond. The department may release the bond at the end of
7 three years after the issuance of the bond if all questions as to the
8 ownership of the motorboat have been answered to the satisfaction of the
9 department unless the department has been notified of the pendency of an
10 action to recover on the bond. If the currently valid certificate of
11 title is surrendered to the department, the department may release the
12 bond prior to the end of the three-year period.
13 (4) The department shall include the following statement on a bonded
14 certificate of title issued pursuant to this section and any subsequent
15 title issued as a result of a title transfer while the bond is in effect:
16 NOTICE: THIS MOTORBOAT MAY BE SUBJECT TO AN UNDISCLOSED INTEREST,
17 BOND NUMBER ............ .
18 (5) The department shall recall a bonded certificate of title if the
19 department finds that the application for the title contained a false
20 statement or if a check presented by the applicant for fees pursuant to
21 this section is returned uncollected by a financial institution.
22 (6)(a) Any applicant for a bonded certificate of title shall provide
23 written notice to any party with a secured interest in the motorboat that
24 is the subject of the application. Such written notice shall be provided
25 to the last-known address of each such party through certified mail with
26 return receipt requested and shall include a notice that the security
27 interest will be discharged if the party fails to respond within thirty
28 days after receiving the notice. If the lienholder responds, the response
29 shall be presented to the department along with the written notice and
30 certified mail receipt.
31 (b) Issuance of a bonded certificate of title shall extinguish any
