15 2024, is amended to read:
16 60-4,122 (1) Except as otherwise provided in subsections (2), (3),
17 and (8) of this section, no original or renewal operator's license shall
18 be issued to any person until such person has demonstrated his or her
19 ability to operate a motor vehicle safely as provided in section
20 60-4,114.
21 (2) Except as otherwise provided in this section and section
22 60-4,127, any person who renews his or her Class O or Class M license
23 shall demonstrate his or her ability to drive and maneuver a motor
24 vehicle safely as provided in subdivision (3)(b) of section 60-4,114 only
25 at the discretion of department personnel, except that a person required
26 to use bioptic or telescopic lenses shall be required to demonstrate his
27 or her ability to drive and maneuver a motor vehicle safely each time he
28 or she renews his or her license.
29 (3) Any person who renews his or her Class O or Class M license
30 prior to or within one year after its expiration may not be required to
31 demonstrate his or her knowledge of the motor vehicle laws of this state
-34-

LB972 LB972
2026 2026
1 as provided in subdivision (3)(c) of section 60-4,114 if his or her
2 driving record abstract maintained in the computerized records of the
3 department shows that such person's license is not impounded, suspended,
4 revoked, or canceled.
5 (4) Except for operators' licenses issued to persons required to use
6 bioptic or telescopic lenses, any person who renews his or her operator's
7 license which has been valid for fifteen months or less shall not be
8 required to take any examination required under section 60-4,114.
9 (5) Any person who renews a state identification card shall appear
10 before department personnel and present his or her current state
11 identification card or shall follow the procedure for electronic renewal
12 in subsection (9) of this section. Proof of identification shall be
13 required as prescribed in sections 60-484 and 60-4,181 and the
14 information and documentation required by sections 60-484.04 and
15 60-484.07.
16 (6)(a) If a nonresident who applies for an initial operator's
17 license in this state presents a physical or mobile valid operator's
18 license from the individual's state of residence, the department may
19 choose not to require such individual to demonstrate knowledge of the
20 motor vehicle laws of this state.
21 (b) A physical operator's license described in subdivision (a) of
22 this subsection shall be surrendered to the department.
23 (c) Upon issuing an initial operator's license described in
24 subdivision (a) of this subsection, the department shall notify the state
25 that issued the valid operator's license described in subdivision (a) of
26 this subsection to invalidate such license.
27 (7) An applicant for an original operator's license may not be
28 required to demonstrate his or her knowledge of the motor vehicle laws of
29 this state if he or she has been issued a Nebraska LPD-learner's permit
30 that is valid or has been expired for no more than one year. The written
31 examination shall not be waived if the original operator's license being
-35-

LB972 LB972
2026 2026
1 applied for contains a class or endorsement which is different from the
2 class or endorsement of the Nebraska LPD-learner's permit.
3 (8)(a)(i) (8)(a) A qualified licensee as determined by the
4 department may renew his or her Class O or Class M license under this
5 subdivision (a) if such person:
6 (A) Is who is twenty-one years of age or older;
7 (B) Holds a , whose license that expires prior to his or her
8 seventy-second birthday; , and
9 (C) Has who has a digital image and digital signature preserved in
10 the digital system.
11 (ii) A renewal under this subdivision (a) may occur may renew his or
12 her Class O or Class M license twice by electronic means in a manner
13 prescribed by the department using the preserved digital image and
14 digital signature without taking any examination required under section
15 60-4,114 if:
16 (A) Such such renewal is prior to or within one year after the
17 expiration of the license;
18 (B) Such person's , if his or her driving record abstract maintained
19 in the records of the department shows that such person's license is not
20 impounded, suspended, revoked, or canceled; , and
21 (C) Such person's if his or her driving record indicates that he or
22 she is otherwise eligible.
23 (iii) A renewal under this subdivision (a) may occur:
24 (A) By electronic means; or
25 (B) In-person at any location approved by the department.
26 (iv) Every licensee, including a licensee who is out of the state at
27 the time of renewal, shall must apply for renewal in person at least once
28 every sixteen years and have a new digital image and digital signature
29 captured.
30 (b) In order to allow for an orderly progression through the various
31 types of operators' licenses issued to persons under twenty-one years of
-36-

LB972 LB972
2026 2026
1 age, a qualified holder of an operator's license who is under twenty-one
2 years of age and who has a digital image and digital signature preserved
3 in the digital system may apply for an operator's license by electronic
4 means in a manner prescribed by the department using the preserved
5 digital image and digital signature if the applicant has passed any
6 required examinations prior to application, if his or her driving record
7 abstract maintained in the records of the department shows that such
8 person's operator's license is not impounded, suspended, revoked, or
9 canceled, and if his or her driving record indicates that he or she is
10 otherwise eligible.
11 (9) Any person who is twenty-one years of age or older and who has
12 been issued a state identification card with a digital image and digital
13 signature may electronically renew his or her state identification card
14 by electronic means in a manner prescribed by the department using the
15 preserved digital image and digital signature. Every person renewing a
16 state identification card under this subsection, including a person who
17 is out of the state at the time of renewal, shall must apply for renewal
18 in person at least once every sixteen years and have a new digital image
19 and digital signature captured.
20 (10) In addition to services available at driver license offices,
21 the department may develop requirements for using electronic means for
22 online issuance of operators' licenses and state identification cards to
23 qualified holders as determined by the department.
24 Sec. 23. Section 60-529, Reissue Revised Statutes of Nebraska, is
25 amended to read:
26 60-529 (1)(a) Prior to July 1, 2027, proof Proof of financial
27 responsibility may be furnished by (i) (1) filing with the department the
28 written certificate of any insurance carrier, duly authorized to do
29 business in this state, or (ii) (2) electronic transmission of a
30 certificate by an insurance carrier, duly authorized to do business in
31 this state, certifying that there is in effect a motor vehicle liability
-37-

LB972 LB972
2026 2026
1 policy for the benefit of the person required to furnish proof of
2 financial responsibility, also known as an SR-22 certificate.
3 (b) Beginning July 1, 2027, proof of financial responsibility shall
4 be furnished by electronic transmission of a certificate by an insurance
5 carrier, duly authorized to do business in this state, certifying that
6 there is in effect a motor vehicle liability policy for the benefit of
7 the person required to furnish proof of financial responsibility, also
8 known as an SR-22 certificate.
9 (2) Such certificate shall give the effective date of the
10 certificate and designate, by explicit description or by appropriate
11 reference, all motor vehicles covered thereby unless the policy is issued
12 to a person who is not the owner of a motor vehicle.
13 (3) A certificate of insurance for fleet vehicles may include, as an
14 appropriate reference, a designation that the insurance coverage is
15 applicable to all vehicles owned by the named insured, or wording of
16 similar effect, in lieu of an explicit description.
17 Sec. 24. Section 60-6,340, Reissue Revised Statutes of Nebraska, is
18 amended to read:
19 60-6,340 (1) No person under the age of sixteen twelve years shall
20 operate a snowmobile in this state unless accompanied by a parent,
21 guardian, or other person over eighteen years of age.
22 (2) No person over the age of twelve years and under the age of
23 sixteen years shall operate a snowmobile in this state unless such person
24 (a) holds a valid snowmobile safety certificate, (b) is accompanied by a
25 person fourteen years of age or over who holds a valid snowmobile safety
26 certificate, or (c) is accompanied by a person over the age of eighteen
27 years.
28 (2) (3) The operator of a snowmobile shall not be required to hold
29 an operator's license.
30 Sec. 25. Section 60-1901, Reissue Revised Statutes of Nebraska, is
31 amended to read:
-38-

LB972 LB972
2026 2026
1 60-1901 (1) A motor vehicle is an abandoned vehicle:
2 (a) If left unattended, with no license plates or a valid In Transit
3 stickers issued pursuant to the Motor Vehicle Registration Act affixed
4 thereto, for more than six hours on any public property;
5 (b) If left unattended for more than twenty-four hours on any public
6 property, except a portion thereof on which parking is legally permitted;
7 (c) If left unattended for more than forty-eight hours, after the
8 parking of such vehicle has become illegal, if left on a portion of any
9 public property on which parking is legally permitted;
10 (d) If left unattended for more than seven days on private property
11 if left initially without permission of the owner, or after permission of
12 the owner is terminated;
13 (e) If left for more than thirty days in the custody of a law
14 enforcement agency after the agency has sent a letter to the last-
15 registered owner and lienholder under section 60-1903.01; or
16 (f) If removed from private property by a municipality pursuant to a
17 municipal ordinance.
18 (2) An all-terrain vehicle, a utility-type vehicle, or a minibike is
19 an abandoned vehicle:
20 (a) If left unattended for more than twenty-four hours on any public
21 property, except a portion thereof on which parking is legally permitted;
22 (b) If left unattended for more than forty-eight hours, after the
23 parking of such vehicle has become illegal, if left on a portion of any
24 public property on which parking is legally permitted;
25 (c) If left unattended for more than seven days on private property
26 if left initially without permission of the owner, or after permission of
27 the owner is terminated;
28 (d) If left for more than thirty days in the custody of a law
29 enforcement agency after the agency has sent a letter to the last-
30 registered owner and lienholder under section 60-1903.01; or
31 (e) If removed from private property by a municipality pursuant to a
-39-

LB972 LB972
2026 2026
1 municipal ordinance.
2 (3) A mobile home is an abandoned vehicle if left in place on
3 private property for more than thirty days after a local governmental
4 unit, pursuant to an ordinance or resolution, has sent a certified letter
5 to each of the last-registered owners and posted a notice on the mobile
6 home, stating that the mobile home is subject to sale or auction or
7 vesting of title as set forth in section 60-1903.
8 (4) For purposes of this section:
9 (a) Mobile home means a movable or portable dwelling constructed to
10 be towed on its own chassis, connected to utilities, and designed with or
11 without a permanent foundation for year-round living. It may consist of
12 one or more units that can be telescoped when towed and expanded later
13 for additional capacity, or of two or more units, separately towable but
14 designed to be joined into one integral unit, and shall include a
15 manufactured home as defined in section 71-4603. Mobile home does not
16 include a mobile home or manufactured home for which an affidavit of
17 affixture has been recorded pursuant to section 60-169;
18 (b) Public property means any public right-of-way, street, highway,
19 alley, or park or other state, county, or municipally owned property; and
20 (c) Private property means any privately owned property which is not
21 included within the definition of public property.
22 (5) No motor vehicle subject to forfeiture under section 28-431
23 shall be an abandoned vehicle under this section.
24 Sec. 26. Section 60-1902, Reissue Revised Statutes of Nebraska, is
25 amended to read:
26 60-1902 If an abandoned vehicle, at the time of abandonment, has no
27 license plates of the current year or a valid In Transit stickers issued
28 pursuant to section 60-376 affixed and is of a wholesale value, taking
29 into consideration the condition of the vehicle, of five hundred dollars
30 or less, title shall immediately vest in the local authority or state
31 agency having jurisdiction thereof as provided in section 60-1904. Any
-40-

